			<p>Written with <persName ref="#ehri_et_abeles_karel">Karel <hi rend="letter-spacing: +2px">Abeles</hi></persName>, born <date
					when="1926-02-04">4. 2. 1926</date>, former <term type="subject" ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-650"
					>prisoner</term> of the <term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-496" type="subject">concentration
					camps</term>
				<placeName ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_ghettos-513">Lodz</placeName>, <placeName
					ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_camps-2">Auschwitz</placeName>, and <placeName
					ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_camps-570">Mauthausen</placeName>, currently residing in <placeName
					ref="http://www.geonames.org/3067696/prague.html">Prague XIII., Ruská</placeName> 934, Jewish nationality, profession <term
					ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-1214" type="subject">student</term>.</p>

			<p>I was born in <placeName ref="http://www.geonames.org/3064288/teplice.html ">Tepl.Šanov</placeName>, where I lived with my <persName
					ref="http://www.holocaust.cz/databaze-obeti/obet/142942-max-abeles/" type="victim">father</persName>, <persName
					ref="http://www.holocaust.cz/databaze-obeti/obet/142950-vilemina-abelesova/" type="victim">mother</persName>, and older <persName
					ref="http://www.holocaust.cz/databaze-obeti/obet/142947-hanus-abeles/" type="victim">brother</persName> until the <term
					ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-1041" type="subject">Sudetenland was annexed</term>. From <date
					when="1938-10">October 1938</date> until <date when="1941-10">October 1941</date> we lived in <placeName
					ref="http://www.geonames.org/3067696/prague.html">Prague</placeName>. That month, Jews were required to <term
					ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-647" type="subject">register</term> and the first <term
					ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-518" type="subject">transports</term> to <placeName
					ref="http://www.geonames.org/798544/republic-of-poland.html">Poland</placeName> took place. Our entire family left on the third
					<term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-518" type="subject">transport</term> to <placeName
					ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_ghettos-513">Lodz</placeName>. It happened like this: we received a <term
					ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/terezin-terms-keyword-jmp-151" type="subject">summons</term> from the <orgName
					ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/jc-organisations-organisation-jmp-3714">Jewish Community</orgName> to come to the
					<placeName ref="http://www.geonames.org/3067696/prague.html">Trade Fair Palace</placeName> in  <placeName
					ref="http://www.geonames.org/3067696/prague.html">Prague</placeName> on <date when="1941-10-23">October 23rd, 1941</date>, with a
				luggage limit of 50 kilograms per person. Our carrier brought our luggage, which was labelled with our number. After all of the
				formalities had been dealt with (handing over the keys to our apartment, and all of our gold, silver, etc.), our citizenship cards
				were stamped with <q><foreign xml:lang="de">Evakuiert</foreign>
					<date when="1941-10-26">26. 10. 1941</date>.</q> We marched past <term
					ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-1216" type="subject">SS</term>
				<foreign xml:lang="de">Grupenführer</foreign> Fidler, who took away all of our <term
					ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-691" type="subject">musical</term> instruments and any luggage that looked
				fancy. At 6 o’clock in the morning, we boarded a passenger train that departed from the  <placeName
					ref="http://www.geonames.org/3078526/bubenec.html">Bubeneč</placeName> train station at 1 o’clock in the afternoon. It traveled
				along a strange route through <placeName ref="http://www.geonames.org/2935022/dresden.html">Dresden</placeName>, <placeName
					ref="http://www.geonames.org/2918987/goerlitz.html">Görlitz</placeName>, <placeName
					ref="http://www.geonames.org/3093692/legnica.html">Liegnitz</placeName>, <placeName
					ref="http://www.geonames.org/3081368/wroclaw.html">Vratislav</placeName>, <placeName
					ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_ghettos-513">Lodz</placeName>. <orgName
					ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/authorities/ehri_cb-428">Schupo</orgName> accompanied us on this journey. The train ride
				lasted 32 hours, and we were given water only once. We got out on some sort of provisional platform. We later learned that this was
					<placeName ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_ghettos-513">Lodz</placeName>. The Jewish police was waiting for us
				on the ramp, and it split us into groups and took us to an empty school <term
					ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-837" type="subject">building</term>. There, 136 <term
					ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-650" type="subject">people</term> were stuffed into a <term
					ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-837" type="subject">room</term> measuring 6x6 meters. Our <term
					ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-837" type="subject">living</term> conditions improved, and thereafter 78
				people would stay in this room. We slept on the floor. I soon became <term
					ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-292" type="subject">sick</term> with <term
					ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-292" type="subject">angina</term>. Right after I got better, my <persName
					ref="http://www.holocaust.cz/databaze-obeti/obet/142950-vilemina-abelesova/">mother</persName>
				<term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-292" type="subject">came down with</term>
				<term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-292" type="subject">pneumonia</term>. Because the <term
					ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-491" type="subject">hospitals</term> were too full, she had to lie on the
				floor while she was <term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-292" type="subject">sick</term>. The rainy autumn
				weather, the abnormal <term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-837" type="subject">accommodations</term>, and the
				overcrowded <term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-837" type="subject">living</term> conditions produced a lot
				filth and made many people <term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-292" type="subject">sick</term>. After three
				weeks, we were all <term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/terezin-terms-keyword-jmp-213" type="subject"
					>lice-infested</term> and there was practically nothing we could do to prevent it.</p>
			<p>We <term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-832" type="subject">ate</term> the last of the <term type="subject"
					ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-833">food</term> we brought with us and then went hungry. We received 20
				decagrams of <term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-832" type="subject">bread</term> and one <term
					ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-832" type="subject">soup</term> per day. The <term
					ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/terezin-terms-keyword-jmp-866" type="subject">Polish Jews</term> didn’t help us, not
				a bit. We didn’t get the fuel for heating that we were allotted and received less and worse kinds of <term
					ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-832" type="subject">potatoes</term> and <term
					ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-832" type="subject">vegetables</term> than they did. We were forced to
					<term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-556" type="subject">work</term> hard at night during the winter, and
				as a consequence my <persName ref="http://www.holocaust.cz/databaze-obeti/obet/142942-max-abeles/" type="victim">father</persName>
				became <term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-292" type="subject">ill</term> with <term
					ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-292" type="subject">phlegmon</term> and <term
					ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-745" type="subject">died</term> of exhaustion on <date when="1942-03-05"
					>5. 3. 1942</date>. I <term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-556" type="subject">worked</term> as a
				blacksmith and my <persName ref="http://www.holocaust.cz/databaze-obeti/obet/142947-hanus-abeles/" type="victim">brother</persName> as
				a leatherworker. At the beginning of <date when="1942">1942</date>, there were mass deportations from the <placeName
					ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_ghettos-513">ghetto</placeName>, which emptied many <term
					ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-837" type="subject">apartments</term>, and the <q>collectives</q> were
				gradually shut down. In <date when="1942-06">June 1942</date>, we were given an <term
					ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-837" type="subject">apartment</term>. I <term
					ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-292" type="subject">contracted</term> a bad case of <term
					ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-292" type="subject">hepatitis</term> and I became severely weak. When I
				got better, I was assigned easier <term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-556" type="subject">work</term> in a
				factory that manufactured wooden products. In <date when="1942-08">August 1942</date>, 25,000 Jews from the <placeName
					ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_ghettos-513">ghetto</placeName> were sent to the <term
					ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-499" type="subject">gas chambers</term>. My <persName
					ref="http://www.holocaust.cz/databaze-obeti/obet/142950-vilemina-abelesova/" type="victim">mother</persName> was also supposed to
				be <term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-518" type="subject">transported</term>, but I bribed the Jewish
				police, and so I managed to free my <persName ref="http://www.holocaust.cz/databaze-obeti/obet/142950-vilemina-abelesova/"
					type="victim">mother</persName>. But her mental and physical condition was very poor at the time, and she <term
					ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-745" type="subject">died</term> on <date when="1942-10-12">12. 10.
					1942</date>. My <persName ref="http://www.holocaust.cz/databaze-obeti/obet/142947-hanus-abeles/" type="victim">brother</persName>,
				who at the same time was tied to a bed with serious <term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-292" type="subject"
					>tuberculosis</term>, <term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-745" type="subject">died</term> after having
				suffered greatly on <date when="1942-11-19">19. 11. 1942</date>. I <term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-746"
					type="subject">buried</term> the 3 closest and dearest people to me according to the <term
					ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-756" type="subject">Jewish funeral custom</term>.</p>
			<p>This was a very difficult time for me. After an 11 hour <term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-556"
					type="subject">work</term> shift, I had to wash my own laundry, cook my own meals, and, worse, do my own shopping. I sold
				everything that I had, I earned my living, and that’s how I supported myself. In the autumn of <date when="1943">1943</date> we were
				given permission to send <term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/terezin-terms-keyword-jmp-716" type="subject"
					>parcels</term> to the <placeName ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_ghettos-513">ghetto</placeName>. I received a
					<term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/terezin-terms-keyword-jmp-716" type="subject">parcel</term> from my friend
					<persName ref="http://www.holocaust.cz/databaze-obeti/obet/116278-jindrich-prossnitz/" type="victim">Heinz Prossnitz</persName>
					from <placeName ref="http://www.geonames.org/3067696/prague.html">Prague</placeName> every week, which elevated my spirits as well
				as made me feel good physically. The liquidation of the <placeName ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_ghettos-513"
					>ghetto</placeName> began in <date when="1944-05">May 1944</date>, since the front was advancing. But we didn’t know that the line
				of attack stopped at <placeName ref="http://www.geonames.org/756135/warsaw.html">Warsaw</placeName>. Because we believed that the
					<term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/authorities/ehri_cb-004583" type="subject">Red Army</term> would arrive soon, we ignored
				the order to leave the <placeName ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_ghettos-513">ghetto</placeName> and <term
					ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-262" type="subject">hid</term>. Neither machine guns, nor <pb n="2"
					facs="EHRI-ET-JMP012_02.jpg"/> any other harsh measures against us couldn’t force us to leave the <placeName
					ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_ghettos-513">ghetto</placeName>. We were terribly hungry and this forced us to
				report ourselves for <term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-518" type="subject">transport</term>. On <date
					when="1944-06-22">June 22nd, 1944</date>, we left <placeName ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_ghettos-513"
					>Lodz</placeName> in a cattle car, destination unknown. The next morning, we arrived at a place where the first thing we saw were
				giant <term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-501" type="subject">chimneys</term> with tall flames shooting up
				from them. We were <q>greeted</q> by <term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-650" type="subject"
					>prisoners</term> in <term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-650" type="subject">prison</term> garb and when
				I asked them what is being produced in the factories, they replied with ironic smiles: <q>chocolate</q>. I didn’t believe that, but I
				had no idea that hundreds of thousands of our fathers, mothers, and children were being <term
					ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-501" type="subject">burnt</term> in them. We were in <placeName
					ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_camps-2">Birkenau near Auschwitz</placeName>. After the <term
					ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-411" type="subject">selection</term> process, we were sent to work as
				expert mechanics and dismantled airplanes that had been shot down. <term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-496"
					type="subject">Camp</term> life, as has often been described, set in. I witnessed terrible things. <placeName
					ref="http://www.geonames.org/3057568/slovak-republic.html 81">Hungarian</placeName>, <term
					ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/terezin-terms-keyword-jmp-865" type="subject">Slovak</term>, and <term
					ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/terezin-terms-keyword-jmp-267" type="subject">Theresienstadt transports</term>
				arrived. This lasted until <date when="1945-01">January 1945</date>.</p>
			<p>The <term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/authorities/ehri_cb-004583" type="subject">Russians</term> once again attacked near
					<placeName ref="http://www.geonames.org/3094802/krakow.html">Krakow</placeName> and threatened <placeName
					ref="http://www.geonames.org/3082777/upper-silesia.html">Upper Silesia</placeName>. We were <term
					ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-623" type="subject">evacuated</term> on <date when="1945-01-18">January
					18th</date>. The train connection didn’t exist any longer and so we set out in wooden shoes with blankets and one loaf of <term
					ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-832" type="subject">bread</term> for the journey. We <term
					ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-517" type="subject">walked</term> all night and day and our strength
				disappeared. The only thing we had left was our will and the hope of being <term
					ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-573" type="subject">liberated</term> soon. Hundreds of <term
					ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-745" type="subject">dead</term> bodies of those who <term
					ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-517" type="subject">marched</term> before us and had already <term
					ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-745" type="subject">died</term> lay at the edge of the roads. Finally, on
				the fourth day, we boarded a train somewhere near <placeName ref="http://www.geonames.org/3096472/katowice.html">Katowice</placeName>.
				They squeezed 120 of us into one open car and, without giving us anything to <term
					ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-832" type="subject">eat</term>, we rode for 4 days and 4 nights. We were
				numb, like animals. In <placeName ref="http://www.geonames.org/3070328/moravska-ostrava.html">Mor. Ostrava</placeName> and <placeName
					ref="http://www.geonames.org/3067580/prerov.html">Přerov</placeName>, the inhabitants gave us some <term
					ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-832" type="subject">food</term>. The <term
					ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-1216" type="subject">SS</term> shot at them, but this didn’t stop them and
				they helped us however they could. On <date when="1945-01-27">27. 1. 1945</date>, our <term
					ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-517" type="subject">death</term> transport ended in <placeName
					ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_camps-570">Mauthausen</placeName> near <placeName
					ref="http://www.geonames.org/2772400/linz.html">Linz</placeName>. Without getting anything to <term
					ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-832" type="subject">eat</term>, they sent us off to the hot showers and
				then they made us run naked and wet into an ice storm. We waited for hours until they let us into the <term
					ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-837" type="subject">block</term>. There were 1,200 <term
					ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-650" type="subject">people</term> in the <term
					ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-837" type="subject">building</term>. I didn’t sleep for 4 weeks. The
				Czechs there stuck together and helped us get <term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-832" type="subject"
					>food</term> whenever possible. In <date when="1945-02">February 1945</date>, I was <term type="subject"
					ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-521">transported</term> to <placeName
					ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_camps-585">Gusen</placeName>. This was the worst I have ever suffered. We <term
					ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-556" type="subject">worked</term> in the underground Messerschmitt
				airplane factory under terrible <term type="subject" ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-831">conditions</term>:
				not enough <term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-832" type="subject">food</term>, little sleep, dirt,
				back-breaking and long <term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-556" type="subject">labor</term>, bad air,
				beatings, and cold. I don’t need to go into the details, just the fact that in 3 months the <term
					ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-508" type="subject">camp</term> had to take up a whole new <term
					ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-556" type="subject">workforce</term> because the previous one <term
					ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-745" type="subject">died</term> a <q>natural</q>
				<term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-745" type="subject">death</term> is enough. This means that in each
				block, which had 800 <term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-650" type="subject">people</term>, an average of 10
					<term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-650" type="subject">prisoners</term>
				<term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-745" type="subject">died</term> every day. When I was at my worst, when
				my strength was starting to leave me, we were <term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-573" type="subject"
					>liberated</term>: on <date when="1945-05-05">May 5th</date> the <term
					ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-1029" type="subject">Americans</term> disarmed our guards and all of the
					<term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-650" type="subject">prisoners</term> left the <term
					ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-508" type="subject">camp</term>. I found shelter in the Czech civilian
					<term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-508" type="subject">labor camp</term> in <placeName
					ref="http://www.geonames.org/2772400/linz.html">Linz</placeName>, where I quickly recovered.</p>
			<p>On <date when="1945-05-18">May 18th, 1945</date>, I returned to <placeName ref="http://www.geonames.org/3067696/prague.html"
					>Prague</placeName>. None of my relatives returned. I am the only living member from the part of my family that remained in
				Europe.</p>

			<p><placeName ref="http://www.geonames.org/3067696/prague.html">In Prague</placeName>, on <date when="1945-08-16">16. VIII. 1945</date>
				<persName ref="#ehri_et_abeles_karel">Karel Abeles</persName></p>

			<p>Statement was accepted by:</p>
			<p>
				<persName ref="#ehri_et_kratkova_marta">Marta Kratková</persName>
			</p>

			<p><persName ref="#ehri_et_shek_zeev">Zeev Scheck</persName> Signatures of witnesses</p>
			<p>
				<persName ref="#ehri_et_weinberger_robert">Robert Weinberger</persName>
			</p>
			<p>
				<persName ref="#ehri_et_ehrmannova_alice_renata">Alice Ehrmannová</persName>
			</p>
			<p>On behalf of the archive: <persName ref="#ehri_et_schmiedt_alexander">Alex. Schmiedt</persName></p>

			<p><date when="1945-08-18">18. 8. 1945</date></p>
